From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Nevertheless, despite widespread awareness of the risks, obesity on a global scale is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to increase.
It was in this context that networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases gathered from December 9 to 11 at the Second World Forum of the Alliance for Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate MNT, they should draw inspiration from the movement against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress made.
Although the battle is not yet over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against MNT can help turn back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of the journal The Lancet, described the medical neuroscience community as waiting for "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
While worldwide attention focuses on preventing NTDs, those seeking to control avoidable diseases should look to the ABCs of AIDS-fighting organizations for inspiration.
The first letter that the MNT community must take into account is "A", as in activism.
Any person over the age of 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets and even shut down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
Globally, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the MNT Community must adopt a more daring approach to budgets - the "B" in the movement's strategy against AIDS.
Civic organizations and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The AIDS fight movement was clear about this from the beginning and pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
"C" stands for coalitions: the movements fighting against AIDS quickly realized that progress comes only with multiple supports.
The activists have linked people living with HIV to those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from the public sector in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS fight movement also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to the spread of its support.
Thus, "D," the determining factor for success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make informed decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that have played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
The MNT are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
The commitment - "E" - is what has helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which has championed the key phrase "Nothing about us without us," advocates for the AIDS cause have demanded the representation of existing organizations tasked with addressing the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply integrated into the HIV/AIDS fight movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Disease prevention movements must also develop convincing narratives, and "F" - the formulation of the question - is essential for the AIDS community to gain the support of political leaders.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been presented as a matter of economic justice.
Formulating the narrative in this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
Another equally important formulation of the issue regarding AIDS, a very relevant question for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on people's life choices, rather than on holding the state responsible for healthcare provision and the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease," and gender identity was rooted from the beginning in the DNA of the AIDS fight movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Therefore, the genre must become a focus for efforts in the prevention of MSTs.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic litigation ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS fight movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS throughout the entire alphabet, but we feel it is appropriate to conclude with the letter "H," since human rights have provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases as well.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same goes for the MNT.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS-fighting movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The communities of the MNT and AIDS can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
